s what matters is not the human pain or joy at all but, rather, the play of shadow and light on a live body, the harmony of trifles assembled … in a unique and inimitable way



writes Nabokov in the concluding sentence of his 1925 short story “The Fight.”7 This early expression, forthright yet undogmatic, of what was to remain an enduring aspect of his aesthetic approach, is, I suspect, destined to be quoted often, and not always in context.

